Initial Exploration of Dataset¶

On this part we will explore into the dataset as to what it contains, spefically the column names, and the summary of the aggregate values on each column.

Every song in the dataset contains 41 features categorized by audio analysis, artist information, and song related features.

  • Audio analysis features: tempo, duration, mode, loudness, key, time signature, section start
  • Artist related features: artist familiarlity, artist popularity, artist name, artist location
  • Song related features: releases, title, year, song hotness

Many fields in the dataset were unusable due to old deprecated data. Many data fields were missing and there was no echonest API to fill in data since the API was modified by Spotify. Therefore many fields had to be dropped.

The two features artist ID and mode were altered to be a better reflection of their properties in the dataset. Every artist in the data was uniquely identified by a string, so we decided to do label encoding on them. Mode is whether the song uses a major or a minor key in its production. Though this value is straightforward with a 0 for minor and a 1 for major, there was also a value named mode_confidence that depicted the probability of the mode selected being accurate. With these two values, we combined the features to range from -1 for minor to 1 for major. A value of -1 represents 100% confidence that the key is minor and 1 represents 100% confidence that the key is major. The range of confidences for minor lie between -1 and 0 and the range of confidences for major lie between 0 and 1.

Add Genre data¶

In the original data of the million song dataset, the genre is not provided. However, a pre-made genre data assigned to track_id has been provided by one researcher who has worked with the idenitification of each genre. The genre-track_id data could be found here: http://www.ifs.tuwien.ac.at/mir/msd/partitions/msd-MAGD-genreAssignment.cls.

In [9]:
# Import the track_id, genre_id file into a dataframe

Adding Country data¶

In the original million song dataset, the country is not provided. However, the artist_latitude and artist_longitude columns are provided for us. We could use this to do a reverse geocoding using reverse_geocode, a python library for reverse geocoding latitude and longitude data.

In [15]:
# Library imports
import math, reverse_geocode

# Get the latitude and longitude columns and store in a variable
artist_latitude = data_with_genre['artist_latitude']
artist_longitude = data_with_genre['artist_longitude']

# Create a blank list. We will append reverse geocoded countries
# on this list
countries = []
In [16]:
# On this part, we will do a reverse geocoding of all rows with latitude 
# and longitude data. We then store the reverse geocoded value in 
# a list and append it into the main dataframe later. 
for i in range(len(artist_latitude)):
    # Get the latitude dataframe cell and store in a variable
    latitude = artist_latitude.iloc[i]
    # Get the longitude dataframe cell and store in a variable
    longitude = artist_longitude.iloc[i]
    
    # There are artist_longitude and artist_latitude that are 
    # null so if we detect at least one null of both values 
    # then we skip them and instead, append a blank
    # value in the list.
    if (math.isnan(latitude) or math.isnan(longitude)):
        countries.append('')
    # If both artist_longitude and artist_latitude values 
    # are present, we do a reverse geocoding and append  
    # these values into a dataframe
    else:
        coordinates = (latitude, longitude),
        # Do a reverse geocoding
        country_data = reverse_geocode.search(coordinates)
        # Append to list
        countries.append(country_data[0]['country'])
In [17]:
# We convert the list to a dataframe
country_df = pd.DataFrame(countries)
In [18]:
# Give the dataframe a column name
country_df.columns = ['country']

Song Hotttnesss over the years by specific genres¶

On this part, we will do a data visualization of the song_hotttnesss data over the years on specific genres that are presently heard commonly, namely Pop_Rock, Latin, Rap, Electronic, Country, and RnB.

In [23]:
# Create a new subset dataframe from data_with_genre dataframe with specifif genres
data_with_genre_2 = data_with_genre[data_with_genre.genre_id.isin(['Pop_Rock', 'Latin', 'Rap', 'Electronic', 'Country', 'RnB'])]
# Convert to data to dataframe
data_with_genre_2 = pd.DataFrame(data_with_genre)
# Only select rows with non-zero values in artist_hotttnesss and artist_familiarity
data_with_genre_2 = data_with_genre_2[(data_with_genre_2.artist_hotttnesss != 0) & (data_with_genre_2.artist_familiarity != 0) & (data_with_genre_2.song_hotttnesss != 0) & (data_with_genre_2.year != 0)]

A Focus on Rap: 2Pac vs Biggie¶

On this part, we will be focusing on two rappers, 2Pac and Biggie, and show comparisons in the artist_familiarity and arist_hotttnesss.

In [27]:
# Create a dataframe with rap as the genre_id

# Create as dataframe of all rows rap as the genre_id except 2Pac and Biggie
df_rap_nob2 = df_rap[(df_rap.artist_name != '2Pac') | (df_rap.artist_name != 'The Notorious B.I.G.')]
